The key difference between civil and criminal law is the difference between the parties involved, that is, private law refers to disputes between individuals while public law deals with disputes between an individual and the government. 
Civil (private) Law is that part of law which is concerned with the rights and duties of individuals, private persons, and the civil society as well. Civil law is the oldest type of law, which is still followed widely in many jurisdictions. The purpose and basis of civil law is to protect the rights of both individuals and groups/community. Civil law is applicable to all the transactions between individuals. 
Criminal Law is the branch of law that regulates the legal status of the offenses against the state and its citizens. The criminal law regulates private activity and conduct as well, but only as it is related to a crime for which punishment is to be meted out by a court of law. The term criminal law can be interpreted broadly to include law that regulates an individual’s wrongful conduct against one or more others. The punishment and sentencing of an accused under criminal law is determined by a criminal conviction, not by a voluntary confession of guilt. The Criminal Law is applicable to individuals, and it imposes duties and obligations on them. Some of the main sources and principles of civil law are the common law and the civil law codes. The common law defines the scope and limits of criminal law and the legal rights and duties of members of civil society. The civil law codes outline the rules for settling disputes between individuals, groups, or the state. Some of the main sources and principles of criminal law are the criminal law codes, the penal code, and legal cases. The criminal law codes define the scope and limits of civil law and outline specific criminal offenses. The penal code gives the government power to punish offenses, usually by imposing mandatory sentences. The legal cases define the rules and principles for criminal law decision making and sentencing. Examples of cases that fall under civil law or criminal law include: 
